[4] India
Date: Thu 16 Jan 2020 23:19 IST
Source: The Times of India (TOI), Times News Network (TNN) [edited]
https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/early-start-to-h1n1-season-40-year-old-satara-man-dies/articleshow/73281604.cms


It is still too soon to know how severe this season [2020] will be, but swine flu [influenza A/H1N1] claimed its 1st victim in the city [Pune, Maharashtra] and the state on [10 Jan 2020].

The 40-year-old man from the rural parts of Satara [district, Maharashtra] died after he tested positive for the contagion at KEM Hospital in Rasta Peth [Pune].

Currently, a 64-year-old woman in Pune is critical and undergoing treatment at the intensive care unit of Sahyadri Hospital in the city.

As many as 6 patients from Mumbai, Navi Mumbai, Thane, and Pune have tested positive for the virus in Maharashtra between [1 and 13 Jan 2020].

Symptoms of swine flu [influenza A/H1N1] are similar to a common cold, and people often take it lightly in the initial stages till it turns critical.

In 2019, as many as 2287 people in the state were diagnosed with the H1N1 infection. Of them, 246 people succumbed to the contagion, accounting for a significant mortality rate of 10 percent, calling for vigilance and also initiation of early treatment for influenza-like illness, say experts.

"Scientists at the National Institute of Virology (NIV) confirmed the presence of H1N1 virus in the man's throat swab on [2 Jan 2020]. He succumbed to [influenza A/H1N1]-induced acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) with septicemia around 5:50 am on [10 Jan 2020]. He was diabetic," a doctor from the KEM Hospital said.

The deceased man was from Nirgudi village in Phaltan taluka of Satara district. He had developed influenza-like illness from [24 Dec 2019]. "Initially, he had fever and cough. Later, he developed high grade fever with breathlessness. He was admitted to KEM hospital in Rasta Peth on [28 Dec 2019]. Despite medication, the man's condition kept worsening. He was also kept on ventilator support during the course of treatment," the doctor said.

Experts say that since the symptoms of [influenza A/H1N1] are quite similar to those of a common cold, people often don't take it seriously in the initial stages until it becomes critical.

"An [influenza A/H1N1] flu patient usually suffers from a burning sore throat, abdominal pain, and cough and the additional symptom of shortness of breath. These symptoms should not be dismissed and need to be treated under the supervision of a medical expert," infectious diseases expert Mahesh Lakhe of Columbia Asia Hospital in Kharadi [Pune] said.

He recommended a [quadrivalent] flu vaccine shot before the flu season peaks, especially for those suffering from underlying medical conditions.

[Byline: Umesh Isalkar]

--
